default&#xa0;defaultSummary of our responses to the Select Committee’s Questionsdefault&#xa0;
defaultWe hope that the submission above provides sufficiently clear responses to the main questions posed in the Select Committee’s Call for Evidence, but for avoidance of doubt we respond briefly to them below.      
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat would be the best institutional arrangements for determining the format and style of the debates? default&#xa0;defaultAs we suggest above, we consider the existing arrangements for determining the form and style of the debates are appropriate and fit for purpose.  
default&#xa0;
defaultMore broadly, how can we ensure that the public interest is the primary concern in determining any administrative matters on topics such as: default&#xa0;defaultWho should take part?  And on what basis? default&#xa0;defaultThis should be a matter for the broadcasters to determine, having regard to the requirements of due impartiality and fairness imposed by their respective regulatory Codes and Editorial Standards.   
default&#xa0;
defaultHow many debates should there be? default&#xa0;defaultThis should be a matter for the broadcasters to determine, with appropriate  consultation with the participants.  But the starting point should be the 2010 debates, as a template of what proved to be a successful series of debates.    
default&#xa0;
defaultWhen and where should each of the debates be held, not least taking into account the potential need for different debates at the UK-wide level and at the level of the nations? default&#xa0;defaultThis is a matter for the relevant broadcasters (including the Channel 3 broadcasters for Scotland and Northern Ireland as regards the nation level debates) and the relevant participants to determine.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat should their format be? default&#xa0;
defaultThis is a matter for the broadcasters to determine, with appropriate consultation with the participants.  But the starting point should be the 2010 debates, as a template of what proved to be a successful series of debates.  Revisions to the format should be for the broadcasters and participants to agree, subject to the requirements of fairness and due impartiality.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn what ways does the interaction between existing broadcast regulation, case law, and the potential for judicial review set the parameters for decisions relating to each of these topics? default&#xa0;
defaultSee paragraphs above.  
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat is the appropriate level of openness and transparency in which these questions should be addressed? default&#xa0;defaultSee paragraphs above
default. default&#xa0;
defaultAre such matters best left to the broadcasters and political parties to determine? defaultYes. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIf so, how can it be guaranteed that the public interest plays a decisive role in their negotiations? default&#xa0;defaultSee paragraphs above. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWould such a body ie a debates commission represent the best way of ensuring the public interest is paramount in such matters? default&#xa0;
defaultNo. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat would be the arguments for the establishment of such a body? default&#xa0;
defaultNone are evident to us. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat would be the arguments against the establishment of such a body?default&#xa0;defaultSee paragraphs above
default. default&#xa0;
defaultHow should a new independent body be established? default&#xa0;
defaultSee above as to why we are not in favour of such a body.  
default&#xa0;
defaultHow could it ensure that the relevant broadcasters and political parties would participate and to do so according to its rules and guidance?default&#xa0;
defaultWe do not consider it is appropriate for any body to seek to enforce the participation of political parties in television programming.  It is a matter for them.    
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat principles should guide the body responsible for this system in determining its view on some of the thorny questions it would face e.g. which political parties should participate? default&#xa0;defaultIt is a matter for the broadcasters to decide which political parties should be invited to participate, both in the debate itself, and in any related programming.  Any party that felt itself unreasonably excluded can complain to the relevant regulator, and thereafter to the courts.       
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat relationship should the new body have, if any, with the Electoral Commission? default&#xa0;defaultWe see no rationale for involvement in this process by the Electoral Commission. 
default&#xa0;
defaultOn any one of these questions, what lessons can the UK learn from other democracies with an established tradition of election debates eg. Australia, Canada, Sweden, Norway, USA etc?default&#xa0;defaultGiven the very different traditions of broadcast regulation of these other territories, we take the view that there are relatively limited lessons to be drawn.     
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
